HMIS API API documentation version 1.0.0

https://www.hmislynk.com/hmis-clientapi/rest

Consent Message

/clients/{clientId}/consentmessages get

get

Gets a list of consent messages for the specified client.

get /clients/{clientId}/consentmessages

Gets a list of consent messages for the specified client.

Secured by oauth_2_0

The HMIS API supports OAuth 2.0 for authenticating all API requests.

  • Request
  • Response
  • Security

URI Parameters

  • clientId: required (string)

HTTP status code 200

Body

Type: application/json

Example:

{
  "oAuthMessageGroups": {
    "oAuthMessageGroup": [
      {
        "consentMessage": "Read your basic account information",
        "detailedConsentMessageExists": "false",
        "oAuthMessageItems": {
          "oAuthMessageItem": {
            "consentMessage": "Read your account id, first name, middle name and last name",
            "detailedConsentMessageExists": "false"
          }
        }
      },
      {
        "consentMessage": "read information associated with your account",
        "oAuthMessageItems": {
          "oAuthMessageItem": [
            {
              "consentMessage": "Sample consent message",
              "detailedConsentMessageExists": "false"
            },
            {
              "consentMessage": "sample consent message",
              "detailedConsentMessageExists": "false"
            }
          ]
        }
      }
    ]
  }
}

HTTP status code 404

Body

Type: application/json

Example:

{
  "errors": {
    "error": {
      "code": "CLIENT_NOT_FOUND",
      "message": "the specified client is not found"
    }
  }
}

Secured by oauth_2_0

Headers

  • Authorization: (string)

    Used to send a valid OAuth 2 access token. Do not use an "access_token" query string parameter.

HTTP status code 401

Bad or expired token. This can happen if the user or the HMIS revoked or expired an access token. To fix, you should re- authenticate the user.

HTTP status code 403

Bad OAuth request (wrong consumer key, bad nonce, expired timestamp...). Unfortunately, re-authenticating the user won't help here.

/clients/{clientId}/detailedconsentmessages

/clients/{clientId}/detailedconsentmessages get

get

Gets a list of detailed consent messages for the specified client.

get /clients/{clientId}/detailedconsentmessages

Gets a list of detailed consent messages for the specified client.

Secured by oauth_2_0

The HMIS API supports OAuth 2.0 for authenticating all API requests.

  • Request
  • Response
  • Security

URI Parameters

  • clientId: required (string)

HTTP status code 200

Body

Type: application/json

Example:

{
  "oAuthMessageGroups": {
    "oAuthMessageGroup": {
      "consentMessage": "Consent message for the API",
      "detailedConsentMessage": "some detailed consent message",
      "oAuthMessageItems": {
        "oAuthMessageItem": { "detailedConsentMessage": "This is the detailed consent message" }
      }
    }
  }
}

HTTP status code 404

Body

Type: application/json

Example:

{
  "errors": {
    "error": {
      "code": "CLIENT_NOT_FOUND",
      "message": "the specified client (trusted App) is not found"
    }
  }
}

Secured by oauth_2_0

Headers

  • Authorization: (string)

    Used to send a valid OAuth 2 access token. Do not use an "access_token" query string parameter.

HTTP status code 401

Bad or expired token. This can happen if the user or the HMIS revoked or expired an access token. To fix, you should re- authenticate the user.

HTTP status code 403

Bad OAuth request (wrong consumer key, bad nonce, expired timestamp...). Unfortunately, re-authenticating the user won't help here.

/clients

Operations performed on the set of all HMIS clients within the system, and for adding a new client to the set of clients

/clients get post

get

Searches for client. Returns a list of client ids, based on the query parameters sent. The query parameters are cumulative, so each additional query parameter narrows the search down further.

post

Add a client

get /clients

Searches for client. Returns a list of client ids, based on the query parameters sent. The query parameters are cumulative, so each additional query parameter narrows the search down further.

Secured by oauth_2_0

The HMIS API supports OAuth 2.0 for authenticating all API requests.

  • Request
  • Response
  • Security

Query Parameters

  • CreatedAfter: (date)

    searches for members of the collection created after (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2011
  • CreatedBefore: (date)

    searches for members of the collection created before (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2012
  • UpdatedAfter: (date)

    searches for members of the collection updated after (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2011
  • UpdatedBefore: (date)

    searches for members of the collection updated before (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2012
  • FirstName: (string)

    Example:

    Bill
  • MiddleName: (string)

    Example:

    Frances
  • LastName: (string)

    Example:

    Smith
  • DOB: (date)

    Example:

    10-11-2012

HTTP status code 200

OK – Everything is working.

  • Response

HTTP status code 201

Returns the ID of the newly created client.

Body

Type: application/json

Schema:

{
  "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-04/schema#",
  "id": "/",
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "client": {
      "id": "client",
      "type": "object",
      "properties": {
        "clientId": {
          "id": "clientId",
          "type": "string"
        }
      },
      "required": [
        "clientId"
      ]
    }
  },
  "required": [
    "client"
  ]
}

Example:

{"client": {"clientId": "717661f4-eaa3-4298-8739-789ab8a1f3d1"}}

Bad Request – The request was invalid or cannot be served.

HTTP status code 401

Unauthorized – The request requires user authentication.

Forbidden – The server understood the request, but is refusing it or access is not allowed.

HTTP status code 404

Not found – There is no resource behind the URI.

Unprocessable Entity - Request body is incorrect.

HTTP status code 500

500 – Internal Server Error.

/clients/{client_id} get put delete

get

Gets a client using a URI resource parameter/ID.

put

Updates a specific client specified by the URI resource parameter/ID.

delete

Deletes a specific client specified by the URI resource parameter/ID.

/clients/{client_id}/enrollments get post

Work with enrollments for a particular client.

get

Fetches all the enrollment ids for a given client, or a subset of them, if a query parameter is used.

post

Adds an enrollment for a given client.

get /clients/{client_id}/enrollments

Fetches all the enrollment ids for a given client, or a subset of them, if a query parameter is used.

Secured by oauth_2_0

The HMIS API supports OAuth 2.0 for authenticating all API requests.

  • Request
  • Response
  • Security

URI Parameters

  • Client Identifier: required (string)

    Example:

    ADBC1111211111114111111111D1111V

Query Parameters

  • CreatedAfter: (date)

    searches for members of the collection created after (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2011
  • CreatedBefore: (date)

    searches for members of the collection created before (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2012
  • UpdatedAfter: (date)

    searches for members of the collection updated after (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2011
  • UpdatedBefore: (date)

    searches for members of the collection updated before (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2012

HTTP status code 200

OK – Everything is working.

Type: application/json

Schema:

{
            "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-04/schema#",
            "id": "/",
            "type": "object",
            "properties": {
              "enrollments": {
                "id": "enrollments",
                "type": "object",
                "properties": {
                  "pagination": {
                    "id": "pagination",
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                      "from": {

Not found – There is no resource behind the URI.

Headers

    Used to send a valid OAuth 2 access token. Do not use an "access_token" query string parameter.

HTTP status code 401

Bad or expired token. This can happen if the user or the HMIS revoked or expired an access token. To fix, you should re- authenticate the user.

HTTP status code 403

Bad OAuth request (wrong consumer key, bad nonce, expired timestamp...). Unfortunately, re-authenticating the user won't help here.

Query Parameters

  • CreatedAfter: (date)

    searches for members of the collection created after (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2011
  • CreatedBefore: (date)

    searches for members of the collection created before (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2012
  • UpdatedAfter: (date)

    searches for members of the collection updated after (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2011
  • UpdatedBefore: (date)

    searches for members of the collection updated before (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2012

      "id": "http://jsonschema.net/Dateofengagements",
      "type": "object",
      "properties": {
        "pagination": {
          "id": "http://jsonschema.net/Dateofengagements/pagination",
          "type": "object",
          "properties": {
            "from": {
              "id": "http://jsonschema.net/Dateofengagements/pagination/from",
              "type": "integer"
            },
            "returned": {
              "id": "http://jsonschema.net/Dateofengagements/pagination/returned",
              "type": "integer"
            },
            "total": {
              "id": "http://jsonschema.net/Dateofengagements/pagination/total",
              "type": "integer"
            },
            "maximum": {
              "id": "http://jsonschema.net/Dateofengagements/pagination/maximum",
              "type": "integer"
            },

            }

            "returned",
            "total",
            "maximum",
            "sort"
          ]
        },

          "id": "http://jsonschema.net/Dateofengagements/dateofengagements",

    searches for members of the collection updated after (inclusive) a particular date

/clients/{client_id}/enrollments/{enroll_id}/enrollmentcocs get post

Operations performed on the set of all HMIS enrollmentcocs within the system, and for adding a new enrollmentcoc to the set of enrollmentcocs

get

Searches for enrollmentcoc. Returns a list of enrollmentcoc ids, based on the query parameters sent. The query parameters are cumulative, so each additional query parameter narrows the search down further.

post

Secured by oauth_2_0

Headers

  • Authorization: (string)

    Used to send a valid OAuth 2 access token. Do not use an "access_token" query string parameter.

HTTP status code 401

Bad or expired token. This can happen if the user or the HMIS revoked or expired an access token. To fix, you should re- authenticate the user.

HTTP status code 403

Bad OAuth request (wrong consumer key, bad nonce, expired timestamp...). Unfortunately, re-authenticating the user won't help here.

get /clients/{client_id}/enrollments/{enroll_id}/exits

Fetches all the exit ids for a given enrollment, or a subset of them, if a query parameter is used.

Secured by oauth_2_0

The HMIS API supports OAuth 2.0 for authenticating all API requests.

  • Request
  • Response
  • Security

URI Parameters

  • Client Identifier: required (string)

    Example:

    ADBC1111211111114111111111D1111V
  • Enrollment Identifier: required (string)

    Example:

    ADBC1111211111114111111111D1111V

Query Parameters

  • CreatedAfter: (date)

    searches for members of the collection created after (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2011
  • CreatedBefore: (date)

    searches for members of the collection created before (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2012
  • UpdatedAfter: (date)

    searches for members of the collection updated after (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2011
  • UpdatedBefore: (date)

    searches for members of the collection updated before (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2012

OK – Everything is working.

Type: application/json

                "type": "object",

                  "exits": {
                    "id": "exits",
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {

                        "id": "pagination",
                        "type": "object",

                          },

                            "id": "returned",

                          },

                            "id": "total",

                            "properties": {}
                          }
                        },
                        "required": [
                          "from",
                          "returned",
                          "total",
                          "maximum",
                          "sort"
                        ]
                      },
                      "exits": {
                        "id": "exits",
                        "type": "array",
                        "items": {
                          "id": "0",
                          "type": "object",
                          "properties": {
                            "exitId": {
                              "id": "exitId",
                              "type": "string"
                            },

post /clients/{client_id}/enrollments/{enroll_id}/exits

Adds an exit for a given enrollment.

Secured by oauth_2_0

The HMIS API supports OAuth 2.0 for authenticating all API requests.

  • Request
  • Response
  • Security

URI Parameters

  • Client Identifier: required (string)

    Example:

    ADBC1111211111114111111111D1111V
  • Enrollment Identifier: required (string)

    Example:

    ADBC1111211111114111111111D1111V

Body

Type: application/json

Schema:

{
"$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-04/schema",
"title": "exit",
"type": "object",
"$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-04/schema",
  "required":["ExitID","ProjectEntryID","DateCreated","ExitDate","DateUpdated","UserID"],
"properties": {
  "ExitID": {
    "type": "string",
    "maxLength": 32,
    "minLength": 32
  },
  "ProjectEntryID": {
    "type": "string",
    "maxLength": 32,
    "minLength": 32
  },
  "ExitDate": {
    "type": "string",
    "format": "date-time"
  },
  "Destination": {
    "type": "integer"
  },
  "OtherDestination": {
    "type": "string",
    "maxLength": 50
  },
  "DateCreated": {
    "type": "string",
    "format": "date-time"
  },
  "DateUpdated": {
    "type": "string",
    "format": "date-time"
  },
  "DateDeleted": {
    "type": "string",
    "format": "date-time"
  },
  "UserID": {
    "type": "string",
    "maxLength": 32,
    "minLength": 32}
  }
}

Type: application/json

Schema:

{
          "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-04/schema#",

          "properties": {
            "exit": {
              "id": "exit",
              "type": "object",
              "properties": {
                "exitId": {
                  "id": "exitId",
                  "type": "string"
                }
              },
              "required": [
                "exitId"
              ]
            }
          },
          "required": [
            "exit"
          ]
        }

get /clients/{client_id}/enrollments/{enroll_id}/healthstatuses

Fetches all the healthStatus ids for a given enrollment, or a subset of them, if a query parameter is used.

Secured by oauth_2_0

The HMIS API supports OAuth 2.0 for authenticating all API requests.

  • Request
  • Response
  • Security

URI Parameters

  • Client Identifier: required (string)

    Example:

    ADBC1111211111114111111111D1111V
  • Enrollment Identifier: required (string)

    Example:

    ADBC1111211111114111111111D1111V

Query Parameters

  • CreatedAfter: (date)

    searches for members of the collection created after (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2011
  • CreatedBefore: (date)

    searches for members of the collection created before (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2012
  • UpdatedAfter: (date)

    searches for members of the collection updated after (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2011
  • UpdatedBefore: (date)

    searches for members of the collection updated before (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2012

    searches for members of the collection created after (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

  • CreatedBefore: (date)

    searches for members of the collection created before (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2012
  • UpdatedAfter: (date)

    searches for members of the collection updated after (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2011

HTTP status code 400

Bad Request – The request was invalid or cannot be served.

HTTP status code 403

Forbidden – The server understood the request, but is refusing it or the access is not allowed.

HTTP status code 404

Not found – There is no resource behind the URI.

HTTP status code 500

500 – Internal Server Error

Secured by oauth_2_0

Headers

  • Authorization: (string)

    Used to send a valid OAuth 2 access token. Do not use an "access_token" query string parameter.

HTTP status code 401

Bad or expired token. This can happen if the user or the HMIS revoked or expired an access token. To fix, you should re- authenticate the user.

HTTP status code 403

Bad OAuth request (wrong consumer key, bad nonce, expired timestamp...). Unfortunately, re-authenticating the user won't help here.

Query Parameters

  • CreatedAfter: (date)

    searches for members of the collection created after (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2011
  • CreatedBefore: (date)

    searches for members of the collection created before (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2012
  • UpdatedAfter: (date)

    searches for members of the collection updated after (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2011
  • UpdatedBefore: (date)

    searches for members of the collection updated before (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2012

HTTP status code 400

Bad Request – The request was invalid or cannot be served.

HTTP status code 401

Unauthorized – The request requires user authentication.

HTTP status code 403

Forbidden – The server understood the request, but is refusing it or access is not allowed.

HTTP status code 404

Not found – There is no resource behind the URI.

HTTP status code 422

Unprocessable Entity - Request body is incorrect.

HTTP status code 500

500 – Internal Server Error.

Secured by oauth_2_0

Headers

  • Authorization: (string)

    Used to send a valid OAuth 2 access token. Do not use an "access_token" query string parameter.

HTTP status code 401

Bad or expired token. This can happen if the user or the HMIS revoked or expired an access token. To fix, you should re- authenticate the user.

HTTP status code 403

Bad OAuth request (wrong consumer key, bad nonce, expired timestamp...). Unfortunately, re-authenticating the user won't help here.

  • CreatedAfter: (date)

    searches for members of the collection created after (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2011
  • CreatedBefore: (date)

    searches for members of the collection created before (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2012
  • UpdatedAfter: (date)

    searches for members of the collection updated after (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2011
  • UpdatedBefore: (date)

    searches for members of the collection updated before (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2012

/projects

Operations performed on the set of all HMIS projects within the system, and for adding a new project to the set of projects

/projects get post

get

Searches for project. Returns a list of project ids, based on the query parameters sent. The query parameters are cumulative, so each additional query parameter narrows the search down further.

post

Add a project

get /projects

Searches for project. Returns a list of project ids, based on the query parameters sent. The query parameters are cumulative, so each additional query parameter narrows the search down further.

Secured by oauth_2_0

The HMIS API supports OAuth 2.0 for authenticating all API requests.

  • Request
  • Response
  • Security

Query Parameters

  • CreatedAfter: (date)

    searches for members of the collection created after (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2011
  • CreatedBefore: (date)

    searches for members of the collection created before (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2012
  • UpdatedAfter: (date)

    searches for members of the collection updated after (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2011
  • UpdatedBefore: (date)

    searches for members of the collection updated before (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2012
  • ProjectName: (string)

    Example:

    The Project

OK – Everything is working.

      "properties": {

              "type": "integer"
            },
            "maximum": {
              "id": "http://jsonschema.net/projects/pagination/maximum",
              "type": "integer"
            },
            "sort": {
              "id": "http://jsonschema.net/projects/pagination/sort",
              "type": "object",
              "properties": {}
            }
          },
          "required": [
            "from",
            "returned",
            "total",
            "maximum",
            "sort"
          ]
        },
        "projects": {
          "id": "http://jsonschema.net/projects/projects",
          "type": "array",
          "items": {
            "id": "http://jsonschema.net/projects/projects/0",
            "type": "object",

              "projectId": {
                "id": "http://jsonschema.net/projects/projects/0/projectId",

/projects/{project_id}/affiliations get post

Operations performed on the set of all HMIS affiliations within the system, and for adding a new affiliation to the set of affiliations

get

Searches for affiliation. Returns a list of affiliation ids, based on the query parameters sent. The query parameters are cumulative, so each additional query parameter narrows the search down further.

post

Add a affiliation

Searches for affiliation. Returns a list of affiliation ids, based on the query parameters sent. The query parameters are cumulative, so each additional query parameter narrows the search down further.

  • Response
  • Security

    Example:

    10-11-2011
  • CreatedBefore: (date)

    searches for members of the collection created before (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2012
  • UpdatedAfter: (date)

    searches for members of the collection updated after (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2011
  • UpdatedBefore: (date)

    searches for members of the collection updated before (inclusive) a particular date

    Example:

    10-11-2012

get

Searches for project_coc. Returns a list of project_coc ids, based on the query parameters sent. The query parameters are cumulative, so each additional query parameter narrows the search down further.

      "required": [
        "availabilty",
        "bedtype",
        "hmisparticipatingbeds",
        "householdtype",
        "unitinventory"
      ]
    }
  },
  "required": [
    "inventory"
  ]
}

post

/search/{searchentity}

/search/{searchentity} get

get

The Search API is optimized to find the specific entity you're looking for (e.g., a client, enrollments, etc.).It's designed to find the one result you're looking for (or maybe the few results you're looking for). Currently hmislynk supporting search on 'clients' and 'projects' entities only. Just like searching on Google, you sometimes want to see a few pages of search results so that you can find the item that best meets your needs. HMISLynk Search API provides up to 50 results for each searh. However, the search results can be limited by the client. Note: 1) API currently supports search on client and project entities 2) URIs are /search/clients and /search/projects

get /search/{searchentity}

The Search API is optimized to find the specific entity you're looking for (e.g., a client, enrollments, etc.).It's designed to find the one result you're looking for (or maybe the few results you're looking for). Currently hmislynk supporting search on 'clients' and 'projects' entities only. Just like searching on Google, you sometimes want to see a few pages of search results so that you can find the item that best meets your needs. HMISLynk Search API provides up to 50 results for each searh. However, the search results can be limited by the client. Note: 1) API currently supports search on client and project entities 2) URIs are /search/clients and /search/projects

Secured by oauth_2_0

The HMIS API supports OAuth 2.0 for authenticating all API requests.

  • Request
  • Response
  • Security

URI Parameters

  • searchentity: required (string)

Query Parameters

  • q: (string)

    The search keywords for clients, as well as any qualifiers.Currently supported search fields are first name,middle name,last name,dob,source system id, client's dedup Id and ssn. For search on "date of birth" field the format MM/dd/YYYY should be used for the search keyword. When searched on dedup Id, the API returns the list of all clients (from all the schema years) that has the same dedup Id.

    The seach keywords for projects, as well as any qualifiers. Currenly supported search fields are projectName, projectCommonName, projectId.

  • sort: (string)

    The sort field. Default- results are sorted by "created date".

    Example:

    created date
  • order: (string - default: desc)

    The sort order if sort parameter is provided. One of asc or desc. Default- desc.

    Example:

    desc
  • startIndex: (integer - default: 0)

    The start Index from where the search results should be returned. Default - 0

  • maxItems: (integer - default: 50)

    the number or Items that should be included in the results . Default - 50

    Example:

    50
  • exclude: (string)

    Excludes fields from the search.Currently it suppoted value is "ssi" (to exclude source system id) only.

HTTP status code 200

Body

Type: application/json

Secured by oauth_2_0

Headers

  • Authorization: (string)

    Used to send a valid OAuth 2 access token. Do not use an "access_token" query string parameter.

HTTP status code 401

Bad or expired token. This can happen if the user or the HMIS revoked or expired an access token. To fix, you should re- authenticate the user.

HTTP status code 403

Bad OAuth request (wrong consumer key, bad nonce, expired timestamp...). Unfortunately, re-authenticating the user won't help here.
